note1 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 1, title: "hello", body: "<p>Thanks for checking out CodeBrew!</p><p></p><p>My name is Eric, and I created CodeBrew based on a constant annoyance I was experiencing with my note taking application.</p><p></p><p>When I was trying to take down notes which contained blocks of code, the whole note instantly became convoluted, making it hard to tell where my sentences ended, and when my code examples began:</p><p></p><blockquote><p><em>Example:</em><br>Creating a React Component:</p><ol><li><p>Remember to require React up at the top</p></li><li><p>Create the class to have at least a render function<br>var Noteform = React.createClass({<br> render: function () {<br> return (&lt;div /&gt;);<br> };<br>});</p></li><li><p>Now we can module.exports NoteForm and use it elsewhere</p></li></ol></blockquote><p></p><p>My solution to this pain was to create an application which had all the nice perks of a note taking application (Notebooks, Notes, Tags), but with the added benefit of being able to insert code snippets within your notes, making it easier to differentiate between code and sentences.</p><p></p><p>With CodeBrew, the above example turns into:</p><p></p><p>Creating a React Component:</p><blockquote><ol><li><p>Remember to require React up at the top</p></li><li><p>Create the class to have at least a render function</p><pre><code>var Noteform = React.createClass({\n   render: function () {\n   return (&lt;div /&gt;);\n   };\n});</code></pre></li><li><p>Now we can module.exports NoteForm and use it elsewhere</p></li></ol></blockquote><p></p><p>This is just a quick demo to show you what CodeBrew can do, please feel free to poke around and explore :)</p>"
)

welcome = Tag.create(name: "welcome")

welcome.notes.push(note1)

Notebook.create(user_id: 1, title: "Algorithms")

note2 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 2, title: "Bubble Sort", body: "<ul><li><p>Worst Case Performance: O(n)^2</p></li><li><p>Best Case Performance: O(n)</p></li><li><p>Average Case Performance O(n)^2</p></li></ul><pre><code>def bubble_sort(list)\n  return list if list.size &lt;= 1 # already sorted\n  swapped = true\n  while swapped do\n    swapped = false\n    0.upto(list.size-2) do |i|\n      if list[i] &gt; list[i+1]\n        list[i], list[i+1] = list[i+1], list[i] # swap values\n        swapped = true\n      end\n    end    \n  end\n\n  list\nend</code></pre>")

note3 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 2, title: "Merge Sort", body: "<ul><li><p>Worst Case Performance: O(n log n)</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Best Case Performance: O(n log n)</p></li><li><p>Average Case Performance O(n log n)</p></li></ul><p></p><p>Pseudocode:</p><pre><code>function merge_sort(list m)\n    // Base case. A list of zero or one elements is sorted, by definition.\n    if length of m ≤ 1 then\n        return m\n\n    // Recursive case. First, divide the list into equal-sized sublists\n    // consisting of the even and odd-indexed elements.\n    var left := empty list\n    var right := empty list\n    for each x with index i in m do\n        if i is odd then\n            add x to left\n        else\n            add x to right\n\n    // Recursively sort both sublists.\n    left := merge_sort(left)\n    right := merge_sort(right)\n\n    // Then merge the now-sorted sublists.\n    return merge(left, right)</code></pre>")

note4 = Note.create(user_id: 1, notebook_id: 2, title: "Quick Sort", body: "<ul><li><p>Worst Case Performance: O(n^2)</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Best Case Performance: O(n log n)</p></li><li><p>Average Case Performance O(n log n)</p></li></ul><p></p><p>Pseudocode:</p><pre><code>algorithm quicksort(A, lo, hi) is\n    if lo &lt; hi then\n        p := partition(A, lo, hi)\n        quicksort(A, lo, p – 1)\n        quicksort(A, p + 1, hi)\n</code></pre><pre><code>algorithm partition(A, lo, hi) is\n    pivot := A[hi]\n    i := lo        // place for swapping\n    for j := lo to hi – 1 do\n        if A[j] ≤ pivot then\n            swap A[i] with A[j]\n            i := i + 1\n    swap A[i] with A[hi]\n    return i</code></pre>")

